'''Boyd's shearwater''' ('''''Puffinus boydi'''''), also known as the '''Cape Verde little shearwater''', is a small [[shearwater]] which breeds in the [[Cape Verde]] archipelago of the [[Atlantic Ocean]] some 570&nbsp;km off the coast of [[West Africa]].  The [[Specific name (zoology)|epithet]] commemorates British [[ornithology|ornithologist]] [[Arnold Boyd]].

== Sexual Segregation ==
Females take longer foraging trips and travel further north. This seems to be driven by differing preferences for chlorophyll concentration and sea surface temperature. Overall spacial overlap of sexes is low. However, their diets are the same, consisting of fish, fish larvae, and squid. Both males and females feed chicks, but the males contribute more. This may be because females spend more time incubating eggs and are therefore more deprived of nutrition.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Santos |first1=Ivo dos |last2=Ramos |first2=Jaime A. |last3=Ceia |first3=Filipe R. |last4=Rodrigues |first4=Isabel |last5=Almeida |first5=Nathalie |last6=Antunes |first6=Stefan |last7=Carreiro |first7=Ana R. |last8=Matos |first8=Diana M. |last9=Lopes |first9=Ricardo J. |date=2022-03-15 |title=Sexual Segregation in the Foraging Distribution, Behaviour, and Trophic Niche of the Endemic Boyd's Shearwater (Puffinus lherminieri Boydi) |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.21203/rs.3.rs-1428025/v1 |access-date=2023-09-21 |doi=10.21203/rs.3.rs-1428025/v1 }}</ref>

==Taxonomy==
Boyd's shearwater is sometimes considered a [[subspecies]] of either the [[little shearwater]], [[Audubon's shearwater]] or [[Macaronesian shearwater]].  It has also been shown to be synonymous with the extinct ''Puffinus parvus'' Shufeldt of [[Bermuda]].

